04562nam a22007575i 9780674287655DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742876557 a10.4159/97806742876552doi  a(DE-B1597)634074  a(OCoLC)1341442988  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aLCO0040102bisacsh1 aLu, Xun, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWild Grass and Morning Blossoms Gathered at Dusk /cXun Lu; ed. by Theodore Huters. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tWild Grass -- tMorning Blossoms Gathered at Dusk -- tNotes -- tLu Xun’s Oeuvre -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA brilliant new translation of the short improvisational fiction and memoirs of Lu Xun, the father of modern Chinese literature.This captivating translation assembles two volumes by Lu Xun, the founder of modern Chinese literature and one of East Asia’s most important thinkers at the turn of the twentieth century. Wild Grass and Morning Blossoms Gathered at Dusk represent a pinnacle of achievement alongside Lu Xun’s famed short stories.In Wild Grass, a collection of twenty-three experimental pieces, surreal scenes come alive through haunting language and vivid imagery. These are landscapes populated by ghosts, talking animals, and sentient plants, where a protagonist might come face-to-face with their own corpse. By depicting the common struggle of real and imagined creatures to survive in an inhospitable world, Lu Xun asks the deceptively simple question, “What does it mean to be human?”Alongside Wild Grass is Morning Blossoms Gathered at Dusk, a memoir in eight essays capturing the literary master’s formative years and featuring a motley cast of dislocated characters—children, servants, outcasts, the dead and the dying. Giving voice to vulnerable subjects and depicting their hopes and despair as they negotiate an unforgiving existence, Morning Blossoms affirms the value of all beings and elucidates a central predicament of the human condition: feeling without a home in the world.Beautifully translated and introduced by Eileen J. Cheng, these lyrical texts blur the line between autobiography and literary fiction. Together the two collections provide a new window into Lu Xun’s mind and his quest to find beauty and meaning in a cruel and unjust world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh  aAbject.  aChildhood.  aChinese Literature.  aDawn Blossoms Plucked at Dusk.  aDream literature.  aDream.  aHome.  aHomelessness.  aMemoirs.  aModern Chinese Literature.  aNature.  aProse poems.1 aCheng, Eileen J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuters, Theodore, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311078579140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674287655?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674287655423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674287655/original  a978-3-11-078579-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK